Singapore. 3 Sep 2016. (conf.) 242 cases since 27 Aug 2016.
http://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-zika-singapore-cases-idUSKCN11A0KR

[Genomic analysis indicated that the virus belongs to the Asian lineage and likely evolved from the strain that was already circulating in Southeast Asia and not imported from the Americas.
(http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/zika-cases-in-singapore-top-200/3097624.html). This is the 1st significant outbreak of Zika virus cases reported in Asia in recent years and prompted issuance of a travel advisory by Indonesia for travel to Singapore (http://jakartaglobe.beritasatu.com/news/zika-outbreak-prompts-indonesia-issue-travel-advisory-singapore/).

Maps of Singapore can be accessed at http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/singapore_pol_05.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4467034,150. - Mod.TY]

Malaysia. 3 Sep 2016. (conf.) 1st 2 cases in the country: 1 case imported ex Singapore, 1 case in Sabah locally acquired.
http://www.businessinsider.com/r-malaysia-detects-first-case-of-locally-transmitted-zika-2016-9

[However, this is not the 1st report of a locally acquired Zika virus infection in Malaysia. A published report stated that on 1 Sep 2014 an acute ZIKV infection was diagnosed in a traveler returning from Malaysian Borneo who experienced bilateral hearing difficulties during the course of illness (http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/21/5/14-1960_article#suggestedcitation). Irene Lai is thanked for calling this report to our attention.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Malaysia can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4467034,147. - Mod.TY]

Thailand. 31 Aug 2016. (conf.) at least 97 cases, whereas 5 cases diagnosed per year usually; provinces affected: Chiang Mai, Chanthaburi, Phetchabun and Bung Kan.
http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2016/08/31/thailand-reports-hike-in-zika-cases/

